Project: Odtone - Open Dot Twenty One v0.1 Beta
URL: http://helios.av.it.pt/projects/odtone


Notes
-----

Please refer to the included "odtone-documentation.pdf" file for a
more detailed explanation.


Download
--------

You can download the latest version of Odtone from the following
website:

	http://helios.av.it.pt/projects/odtone

Alternatively, you can check out the latest version from the Odtone
Git repository:

	git	clone http://helios.av.it.pt/projects/odtone/git/ odtone


Dependencies
------------

Odtone depends on a few libraries, which need to be installed before
Odtone can be compiled.

- Boost (version 1.37 or newer): http://www.boost.org
- Sqlite (version 3.5.9 or newer): http://www.sqlite.org


Compilation - Linux
--------------------

Compiling Odtone is as simple as:

		  ./autogen.sh
		  ./configure
		  make


Compilation - Windows
---------------------

Project files are provided for Visual Studio 2008 to build odtone, you will
need to download and install the boost library (instructions to download,
compile and install are provided below). Build targets are currently available
for x86-32, x86-64 and in the future Windows Mobile Platforms.


Boost Library Installation Guide
--------------------------------

1. Download the latest boost library from http://www.boost.org/users/download/ and
bjam binary for your platform. Ubuntu users can install bjam using the following
command:
	$ sudo apt-get install bjam

2. Extract the boost library and navigate to it's root dir in a command line
3. Compile and install:
on windows:
	$ bjam variant=debug link=static runtime-link=static --with-thread --with-system --with-program_options
	$ bjam variant=release link=static runtime-link=static define=_SECURE_SCL=0 cxxflags=/GL linkflags=/LTCG --with-thread --with-system --with-program_options

	- The libraries will be placed at <boost-root>/stage/lib, you can use the
	  --libdir=<LIB_DIR> option to specify another path for the boost library
	  binaries.

	- To build Boost for x86-64 use the option memory-model=64, example:
		$ bjam variant=debug memory-model=64 link=static runtime-link=static --with-thread --with-system --with-program_options

	- You will also need to set the include and library paths in Visual Studio.

on linux:
	$ sudo bjam install --with-thread --with-system --with-program_options

	- The boost library will be automatically detected by the odtone build.
